WEBVTT

00:00:00.700 --> 00:00:05.640
So I'm going to shift us all backwards a little bit to talk about allogeneic transplant again

00:00:05.640 --> 00:00:10.240
with focus on AML and specifically looking at the use of maintenance therapy.

00:00:11.300 --> 00:00:16.140
Now, as we all probably know by now, there's really substantial evidence for giving FLT3

00:00:16.140 --> 00:00:20.860
tyrosine kinase inhibitors, or TKIs, as maintenance therapy post-transplant.

00:00:21.440 --> 00:00:25.940
And this data is actually probably best for serafinib, where we have two large randomized

00:00:25.940 --> 00:00:31.900
phase 3 studies, the SOAR main study with 83 patients and the Chinese study with 202

00:00:31.900 --> 00:00:37.220
patients, both of which showed a significant reduction in relapse at two and one years

00:00:37.220 --> 00:00:39.120
respectively with respect to placebo.

00:00:39.940 --> 00:00:44.560
Moving sort of clockwise around this slide, we also have the MORFO study, which most people

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:47.780
here are probably very familiar with, of giltaritinib versus maintenance.

00:00:48.340 --> 00:00:53.900
And while this didn't actually show a significantly significant reduction in relapse with a p-value

00:00:53.900 --> 00:00:55.580
of 0.0518.

00:00:55.940 --> 00:00:58.520
I think we all audibly sighed when we saw that.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:02.740
There were differences among pre-specified subsets, such as MRD positivity.

00:01:03.480 --> 00:01:07.340
And then finally, in RADIUS, which looked at mitostaurin maintenance, there was a numerical

00:01:07.340 --> 00:01:10.300
reduction in relapse, even if that wasn't significant.

00:01:11.600 --> 00:01:15.600
Now, there are a lot of caveats to these studies, and I could probably give in a separate talk

00:01:15.600 --> 00:01:19.860
altogether, just talking about the problems with the way these were designed or some nuances.

00:01:20.680 --> 00:01:25.940
But suffice it to say, this is enough data to convince the NCCN that all patients with

00:01:25.940 --> 00:01:31.280
FLT3 FLT3-positive AML undergoing transplant should be at least considered for some sort

00:01:31.280 --> 00:01:32.220
of maintenance therapy.

00:01:33.380 --> 00:01:37.100
However, as I mentioned before, there's a lot of nuances to these studies.

00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:39.880
Patients on these trials were younger and fitter.

00:01:39.880 --> 00:01:42.800
The median age was actually 35 to 54.

00:01:43.660 --> 00:01:48.660
Many patients were TKI-naive, had never seen a FLT3 inhibitor prior to maintenance, and

00:01:48.660 --> 00:01:51.300
many trials restricted to patients in CR1.

00:01:52.140 --> 00:01:54.460
Obviously, patients in the real world are different.

00:01:54.760 --> 00:01:55.680
Our patients are older.

00:01:55.880 --> 00:01:57.000
They have more comorbidities.

00:01:57.540 --> 00:01:59.980
Pillow burden and polypharmacy are real considerations.

00:02:00.580 --> 00:02:01.700
As is tolerability.

00:02:02.160 --> 00:02:08.480
Even in these sort of idealized clinical trial situations, 22 to 59% of patients either had

00:02:08.480 --> 00:02:12.920
to stop maintenance therapy altogether or reduce dose because they couldn't tolerate

00:02:12.920 --> 00:02:13.700
the side effects.

00:02:14.140 --> 00:02:17.180
And remember, these are patients who, in theory, are cured of these diseases.

00:02:18.320 --> 00:02:22.480
Because of that, I wanted to look at the use of maintenance with a special focus on

00:02:22.480 --> 00:02:25.820
tolerability in the real world and did this using administrative clients.

00:02:25.820 --> 00:02:27.820
I'm going to talk about the use of maintenance in the real world and the use of the use of

00:02:27.820 --> 00:02:28.820
claims data.

00:02:28.820 --> 00:02:29.820
I specifically looked at two outcomes at interest.

00:02:29.820 --> 00:02:30.820
The first is adherence.

00:02:30.820 --> 00:02:31.820
And you can think of this as, were there any gaps in prescribing?

00:02:31.820 --> 00:02:32.820
How many potential days in which a patient could be on maintenance were covered by a

00:02:32.820 --> 00:02:33.820
prescription?

00:02:33.820 --> 00:02:34.820
Based on the solid tumor literature for oral oncology drugs, perfect adherence is considered

00:02:34.820 --> 00:02:35.820
at least 80% of potential days are covered by a prescription for a drug.

00:02:35.820 --> 00:02:36.820
Next, I looked at persistence, or how long do patients stay on therapy?

00:02:36.820 --> 00:02:37.820
And again, borrowing from the previous slide, I looked at the use of maintenance in the

00:02:37.820 --> 00:02:38.820
real world.

